Most v1.0 functions completed by 12/29/2024
NOTES:
The oVirt REST API has a combination of what I call base (or primary) objects, and secondary objects that require a 
	base object to "pivot" from. OR Combo objects that can be either a base or secondary Type
There are several connection management functions that work together to handle connection continuity.
This Module starts with authentication to an oVirt server, by providing a Username/Password and receiving a token in Return
Typically the tokens expire after 30 minutes of inactivity, or on the date that is returned with the token.
I created a connection management object called $global:oVirtConnections that stores an ArrayList of connection objects, one for each oVirt server
Each connection object is assembled from the data returned during the authentication process, coupled with additional meta data related to 
the oVirt server, credentials, and TimeStamp info.
Most of the functions that query and send changes to the oVirt server, call a function that updates the last used time stamp, in order to 
know when the Token should expire and trigger a refresh.

Most of the Get-xxxx functions gather basic object info and forward to the Get-oVirtObject function, to reduce code duplication
Most of the rest of the New-xxxx, Set-xxxx, Remove-xxxx functions are custom and unique. At some point I might re-write those to 
behave more like the Get functions.

There are also "helper" functions, some exported, some not, that only work within the PS scope of the module.
They handle things like converting Epoch time, handling SSL/TLS settings and certificates, and more

There is a section for creating classes for most of the oVirt objects, to improve object type detection, metadata, base/secondary management, 
methods to retrieve related objects, and update the objects data.

There is a section storing a few object lookup tables that help define the parameters for the Get-oVirtObject function, Time Zones, CPU and BIOS Types, Object default display properties, and More

Some of the functions were written and not tested yet because their features do not exist on the systems available during authoring this module, but should be a good framework for future updates.

NOTE: Based on OLVM version 4.5.4 or higher, some features may not work with previous versions
