						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) `$_: $($_ | Out-String)"
					}
				}
			}
		}
		
		IF($PSBoundParameters['oStorageDomainUid']){
			$PSBoundParameters['oStorageDomainUid'] | %{
				$UidUrl = [Uri]$_
				#$oStorageDomainObjects = Get-oStorageDomain -Id ($UidUrl.Segments[($UidUrl.Segments.count -1)]) -oVirtServerName ($UidUrl.Host) -EA SilentlyContinue
				$oStorageDomainObjects += (Get-oUri -Uri $_ -EA SilentlyContinue | ?{$_} | %{Convert-RestResponseTooVirtObject -InputObject $_ -ObjectType "oStorageDomain" -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName})
				IF($oStorageDomainObjects){$oStorageDomainObjects | Select -Unique -ExpandProperty oVirtServer | Sort -Unique | %{Update-oVirtServer_LastUsedTime -oVirtServerName $_}}
			}
		}ElseIF($PSBoundParameters['oStorageDomainId']){
			ForEach($ItemId in $PSBoundParameters['oStorageDomainId']){
				IF($PSBoundParameters['oVirtServerName']){
					$oStorageDomainObjects += Get-oStorageDomain -oVirtServerName $PSBoundParameters['oVirtServerName'] -Id $ItemId -EA SilentlyContinue
				}Else{
					$oStorageDomainObjects += Get-oStorageDomain -Id $ItemId -EA SilentlyContinue
				}
				IF($oStorageDomainObjects){$oStorageDomainObjects | Select -Unique -ExpandProperty oVirtServer | Sort -Unique | %{Update-oVirtServer_LastUsedTime -oVirtServerName $_}}
			}
			#$oStorageDomainObjects = $oStorageDomainObjects | Sort -Unique
		}ElseIF($PSBoundParameters['oStorageDomain']){
			ForEach($Item in $PSBoundParameters['oStorageDomain']){
				SWITCH($Item){
					{($_ -IS [System.String]) -OR ($_.GetType().Name -eq "String")}{
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) oStorageDomain is String"
						IF($PSBoundParameters['oVirtServerName']){
							$oStorageDomainObjects += Get-oStorageDomain -oVirtServerName $PSBoundParameters['oVirtServerName'] -Name $Item -EA SilentlyContinue
						}Else{
							$oStorageDomainObjects += Get-oStorageDomain -Name $Item -EA SilentlyContinue
						}
						IF($oStorageDomainObjects){$oStorageDomainObjects | Select -Unique -ExpandProperty oVirtServer | Sort -Unique | %{Update-oVirtServer_LastUsedTime -oVirtServerName $_}}
					}
					{($_ -IS [oStorageDomain]) -OR ($_.GetType().Name -eq "oStorageDomain")}{
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) oStorageDomain is [oStorageDomain]"
						$oStorageDomainObjects += $Item
					}
					DEFAULT{
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) DEFAULT TYPE SECTION"
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) oStorageDomain is GetType: $($_.GetType() | Out-String)"
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) `$_: $($_ | Out-String)"
					}
				}
			}
		}
		
		$oTemplateSpecs = [PSCustomObject]@{}
		$oVmSpecs = [PSCustomObject]@{}
		IF($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey('Name')){ $oTemplateSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'name' -Value $PSBoundParameters['Name'] }
		IF($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey('Comment')){ $oTemplateSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'comment' -Value $PSBoundParameters['Comment'] }
		IF($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey('Description')){ $oTemplateSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'description' -Value $PSBoundParameters['Description'] }
		
		IF($oVMObjects){
			IF($oVMObjects.count -gt 1){$oVMObject = $oVMObjects | Out-GridView -Title "Select oVM to Use As oTemplate Source" -OutputMode Single}Else{$oVMObject = $oVMObjects}
			IF($oVMObject.status -eq "down"){
				$oVmSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'id' -Value $oVMObject.Id
				$oVMObject.GetoDisks() | Out-Null
				IF($oClusterObjects){
					IF($oClusterObjects.count -gt 1){$oClusterObject = $oClusterObjects | Out-GridView -Title "Select oVM to Use As oTemplate Source" -OutputMode Single}Else{$oClusterObject = $oClusterObjects}
					$oTemplateSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'cluster' -Value $([PSCustomObject]@{"id"=$oClusterObject.Id})
				}Else{
					$oVMObject.GetoClusters() | Out-Null
					$oClusterObject = $oVMObject.cluster
					$oTemplateSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'cluster' -Value $([PSCustomObject]@{"id"=$oClusterObject.Id})
				}
				IF($oCpuProfileObjects){
					IF($oCpuProfileObjects.count -gt 1){$oCpuProfileObject = $oCpuProfileObjects | Out-GridView -Title "Select oVM to Use As oTemplate Source" -OutputMode Single}Else{$oCpuProfileObject = $oCpuProfileObjects}
					$oTemplateSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'cpu_profile' -Value $([PSCustomObject]@{"id"=$oCpuProfileObject.Id})
				}Else{
					$oCpuProfileObject = $oVMObject.cpu_profile
					$oTemplateSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'cpu_profile' -Value $([PSCustomObject]@{"id"=$oCpuProfileObject.Id})
				}
				IF(!($oVMObject.oDisk)){
					<#
						The template can be created as a sub-version of an existing template. This requires the name and vm attributes for the new template, and the base_template and version_name attributes for the new template version. The base_template and version_name attributes must be specified within a version section enclosed in the template section. Identify the virtual machine with the id or name attributes.

						<template>
						  <name>mytemplate</name>
						  <vm id="123"/>
						  <version>
							<base_template id="456"/>
							<version_name>mytemplate_001</version_name>
						  </version>
						</template>
					
					#I think this would require also getting an existing oTemplate's Id ?? Not in the UI so not sure how that would work
					#Greyed out if oDisk Attached
					IF($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey('CreateAsATemplateSubVersion')){
						$oTemplateSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'version' -Value $([PSCustomObject]@{"version_name"=$PSBoundParameters['CreateAsATemplateSubVersion']})
					}Else{
						$oTemplateSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'version' -Value $Null
					}
					#>

				}ElseIF($oVMObject.oDisk.Count -ge 1){
					ForEach($oDisk in $oVMObject.oDisk){
						$oDiskAttachmentSpecs = [PSCustomObject]@{}
						$oDiskAttachmentSpec = [PSCustomObject]@{}
						$oDiskSpecs = [PSCustomObject]@{}
						$oDiskSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'id' -Value $oDisk.id
						IF($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey('Alias')){ $oDiskSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'name' -Value $PSBoundParameters['Alias'] }
						IF($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey('Format')){ $oDiskSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'format' -Value $PSBoundParameters['Format'] }
						IF($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey('Sparse')){ $oDiskSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'sparse' -Value $PSBoundParameters['Sparse'] }
						IF($oStorageDomainObjects){
							IF($oStorageDomainObjects.count -gt 1){$oStorageDomainObject = $oStorageDomainObjects | Out-GridView -Title "Select oStorageDomain to Use As oTemplate Target" -OutputMode Single}Else{$oStorageDomainObject = $oStorageDomainObjects}
						}Else{
							$oStorageDomainObject = $oDisk.storage_domains.storage_domain
						}
						$oDiskSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'storage_domains' -Value $([PSCustomObject]@{"storage_domain" = @($([PSCustomObject]@{"id"=$oStorageDomainObject.Id}))})
						#IF($oDisk.provisioned_size){ $oDiskSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'provisioned_size' -Value $oDisk.provisioned_size }
						$oDiskAttachmentSpec | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'disk' -Value $oDiskSpecs
						$oDiskAttachmentSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'disk_attachment' -Value @($oDiskAttachmentSpec)
					}
					$oTemplateSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'disk_attachments' -Value $oDiskAttachmentSpecs
				}
				IF($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey('SealTemplate')){ $oTemplateSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'seal' -Value $PSBoundParameters['SealTemplate'] }
				$oTemplateSpecs | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'vm' -Value $oVmSpecs
				
				#Send to Server
				Resolve-oVirtConnection -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName | Out-Null
				$Token = $(($oVirtConnections | ?{$_.Name -eq $oVirtServerName}).ExtensionData.access_token)
				$Headers = @{"Accept" = "application/json";"Authorization" = "Bearer $($Token)"; "All-Content"="true"}
				#$Headers = @{"Accept" = "application/xml";"Authorization" = "Bearer $($Token)"; "All-Content"="true"}
				#POST /ovirt-engine/api/templates
				$Uri = $BaseURL + "/ovirt-engine/api/templates"
				IF($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey('CopyVMPermissions')){
					IF($PSBoundParameters['CopyVMPermissions'] -eq $True){$Uri = $Uri + "?clone_permissions=true"}Else{$Uri = $Uri + "?clone_permissions=false"}
				}
				$Method = "POST"
				$JsonBody = $oTemplateSpecs | ConvertTo-Json -Depth 50
				#$JsonBody | ConvertFrom-Json2Xml
				#($oObjectSpecs | ConvertTo-Json | ConvertFrom-Json2Xml)
				Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand): Submitting Json to Create oTemplate"
				Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand): `$Uri [$($Uri | Out-String)]"
				Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand): JSON: [$($JsonBody | Out-String)]"
				$NewoTemplate = $Null
				TRY{$NewoTemplate = Invoke-RestMethod -Uri $Uri -Headers $Headers -Method $Method -Body $JsonBody -ContentType "application/json" -EV WebError}Catch{$FormattedWebError = (Format-WebError -WebError $WebError -Body $JsonBody -Uri $Uri); $OutPutItems.Add($FormattedWebError) | Out-Null; Write-Error $FormattedWebError}
				IF($NewoTemplate){
					Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand): Created oTemplate"
					$ThisoTemplate = (Convert-RestResponseTooVirtObject -InputObject (Get-oUri -RESTUri $NewoTemplate.href -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName) -ObjectType "oTemplate" -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName)
					$OutPutItems.Add($ThisoTemplate) | Out-Null
					Update-oVirtServer_LastUsedTime -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName
				}Else{
					Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand): Error [$($WebError | Out-String)]"
				}
				
				IF(($PSBoundParameters['AllowAllUsersToAccessThisTemplate']).IsPresent -eq $True){
					$oTemplateoPermissions = $Null
					$oTemplateoPermissions = $ThisoTemplate | Get-oPermission
					IF(($PSBoundParameters['AllowAllUsersToAccessThisTemplate']).IsPresent -eq $True){
						IF($PSBoundParameters['AllowAllUsersToAccessThisTemplate'] -eq $True){
							$oTemplateoPermissions = $Null
							$oTemplateoPermissions = $ThisoTemplate | Get-oPermission
							$oTemplateoPermissions.GetRelated()
							$AuthSource = $Null
							$UserTemplateBasedVmoPermission = $Null; $UserTemplateBasedVmoPermission = $oTemplateoPermissions | ?{($_.role.name -eq "UserTemplateBasedVm")} | ?{($_.User.Id -eq $oVirt.authenticated_user.id) -AND ($_.User.domain.Id -eq $oVirt.authenticated_user.domain.id) -AND ($_.User.oVirtServer -eq $oVirt.authenticated_user.oVirtServer)}
							IF($UserTemplateBasedVmoPermission){
								($Nada = $UserTemplateBasedVmoPermission | Remove-oPermission -Confirm:0) | Out-Null
								($Nada = New-oPermission -oObject $ThisoTemplate -Group "Everyone" -oRole $UserTemplateBasedVmoPermission.role -oVirtServerName $ThisoTemplate.oVirtServer -AuthSource "internal-authz" -Confirm:0) | Out-Null
							}
						}
					}
				}
			}Else{Write-Warning "Provided oVM status [$($oVMObject.status)] is NOT in the required state or 'down', quitting..."; BREAK}
		}Else{Write-Warning "Provided oVM Not Found, quitting..."; BREAK}
	}
	End{IF($OutPutItems.Count -gt 1){$OutPutItems}ElseIF($OutPutItems.Count -eq 1){$OutPutItems[0]}}
}

Function New-oUser{
	<#
		.SYNOPSIS
			This function creates/imports a new oUser, on an oVirt Server system.
		.DESCRIPTION
			This function creates a new oUser, on a oVirt Server system for the local "internal-authz" account management or imports from an LDAP/Active Directory Identity Source.
			Returns the instanitated oUser from the oVirt Server.
			It does NOT create a user in an external Identity Source.
		.PARAMETER Name
			The Name(s) of oUser
			Can use Wildcard '*'
		.PARAMETER oDomain
			The Name of the Source oDomain for the new oUser(s)
		.PARAMETER oDomainId
			The Id of the Source oDomain for the new oUser(s)
		.PARAMETER oDomainUid
			The Uid of the Source oDomain for the new oUser(s)
		.PARAMETER oVirtServerName
			The Name of the target oVirt Server (Oracle Linux Virualtization Manager)(OLVM) system
		.EXAMPLE
			PS> New-oUser -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName -Name "MyUser" -oDomain "oDomain"
				Creates a new oUser with the provided Name
		.INPUTS
			[System.String]
			[oDomain]
		.OUTPUTS
			[System.String]
			[PSCustomObject]
			[oUser]
		.NOTES
			See David A. Stewart <itsavant@gmail.com>.
			Version 1.0		9/6/2024
		.LINK
			See David A. Stewart <david.a.stewart@Oracle.com>.
		.LINK
			https://ovirt.github.io/ovirt-engine-api-model/4.5/#types/user
			https://ovirt.github.io/ovirt-engine-api-model/4.5/#services/user
			https://ovirt.github.io/ovirt-engine-api-model/4.5/#services/users
			Get-oUser
			Remove-oUser
			Get-Help
	#>
	[CmdletBinding(SupportsShouldProcess, ConfirmImpact = 'High', DefaultParameterSetName = 'Set01')]
	Param(
		[Parameter(Mandatory=$True, ValueFromPipeline=$True, ValueFromPipelineByPropertyName=$True, Position=0)]
			[System.String]$UserName,
		[Parameter(Mandatory=$True, ValueFromPipeline=$False, ValueFromPipelineByPropertyName=$True, ParameterSetName="Set01", Position=1)]
			[ValidateScript({($_).GetType().Name -match 'oDomain|String'})]$oDomain,
		[Parameter(Mandatory=$True, ValueFromPipeline=$False, ValueFromPipelineByPropertyName=$True, ParameterSetName="Set02")]
				[ValidatePattern('^[0-9a-zA-Z]{8}-[0-9a-zA-Z]{4}-[0-9a-zA-Z]{4}-[0-9a-zA-Z]{4}-[0-9a-zA-Z]{12}$')]
			[System.String]$oDomainId,
		[Parameter(Mandatory=$True, ValueFromPipeline=$False, ValueFromPipelineByPropertyName=$True, ParameterSetName="Set03")]
			[ValidateScript({IF(([Uri]$_).AbsoluteUri -eq $Null){Throw [System.Management.Automation.ValidationMetadataException] "The input Uid: `'${_}`' is not a valid Uid"}Else{$True}})]
			[System.String]$oDomainUid,
		
		#oVirtServerName
		[Parameter(Mandatory=$False, ValueFromPipeline=$False, ValueFromPipelineByPropertyName=$True,  HelpMessage="oVirtServerName (Name or IP)")]
			[Alias('oVirtServer')]
			[System.String]$oVirtServerName
	)
	Begin{
		Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand): Running"
		IF($oVirtServerName){
			$BaseURL = "https://$($oVirtServerName)"
		}Else{
			$oVirtServerName = $oVirtConnections[0].oVirtServerName
			$BaseURL = "https://$($oVirtServerName)"
		}
		$OutPutItems = [System.Collections.Generic.List[PSobject]]@()
	}
	Process{
		Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) Parameter Set: [$($PSCmdlet.ParameterSetName)]"
		Write-Verbose "Parameter Set: [$($PSCmdlet.ParameterSetName)]"
		IF($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey('oVirtServerName')){$oVirtServerNames = $PSBoundParameters['oVirtServerName']}Else{$oVirtServerNames = Show-oVirtConnection | Select -ExpandProperty oVirtServerName}
		$OutPutItems = [System.Collections.ArrayList]@()
		ForEach($oVirtServerName in $oVirtServerNames){
			$BaseURL = "https://$($oVirtServerName)"
			IF($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey("oDomain")){
				SWITCH($PSBoundParameters['oDomain']){
					{$_ -IS [System.String]}{
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) oDomain is String"
						IF($PSBoundParameters['oVirtServerName']){
							$oDomain = Get-oDomain -Name $PSBoundParameters['oDomain'] -oVirtServerName $PSBoundParameters['oVirtServerName'] -EA SilentlyContinue
						}Else{
							$oDomain = Get-oDomain -Name $PSBoundParameters['oDomain'] -EA SilentlyContinue -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName
						}
					}
					{$_.GetType().Name -eq "String"}{
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) oDomain GetType equals String"
						IF($PSBoundParameters['oVirtServerName']){
							$oDomain = Get-oDomain -Name $PSBoundParameters['oDomain'] -oVirtServerName $PSBoundParameters['oVirtServerName'] -EA SilentlyContinue
						}Else{
							$oDomain = Get-oDomain -Name $PSBoundParameters['oDomain'] -EA SilentlyContinue -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName
						}
					}
					{$_ -IS [oDomain]}{
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) oDomain is [oDomain]"
						$oDomain = $PSBoundParameters['oDomain']
					}
					{$_.GetType().Name -eq "oDomain"}{
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) oDomain GetType equals [oDomain]"
						$oDomain = $PSBoundParameters['oDomain']
					}
					DEFAULT{
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) DEFAULT TYPE SECTION"
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) oDomain is GetType: $($_.GetType() | Out-String)"
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand) `$_: $($_ | Out-String)"
					}
				}
			}ElseIF($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey("oDomainId")){
				IF($PSBoundParameters['oVirtServerName']){
					$oDomain = Get-oDomain -Id $PSBoundParameters['oDomainId'] -oVirtServerName $PSBoundParameters['oVirtServerName'] -EA SilentlyContinue
				}Else{
					$oDomain = Get-oDomain -Id $PSBoundParameters['oDomainId'] -EA SilentlyContinue -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName
				}
			}ElseIF($PSBoundParameters.ContainsKey("oDomainUid")){
				$UidUrl = [Uri]$oDomainUid
				$oDomain = Get-oDomain -Id ($UidUrl.Segments[($UidUrl.Segments.count -1)]) -oVirtServerName ($UidUrl.Host) -EA SilentlyContinue
			}
			IF($oDomain){
				$oDomain | Select -Unique -ExpandProperty oVirtServer | Sort -Unique | %{Update-oVirtServer_LastUsedTime -oVirtServerName $_}
				IF($oDomain.GetType().Name -eq "oDomain"){
					$oUserSpec = [PSCustomObject]@{}
					IF($oDomain.Name -eq "internal-authz"){
						$oUserSpec | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'user_name' -Value "$($PSBoundParameters['UserName'])@$($oDomain.name)"
						#$oUserSpec | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'domain' -Value $([PSCustomObject]@{'id'=$oDomain.Id})
						$oUserSpec | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'domain' -Value $([PSCustomObject]@{'name'=$oDomain.name})
					}ElseIF($oDomain.Name -Match '.'){
						$oUserSpec | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'principal' -Value "$($PSBoundParameters['UserName'])@$($oDomain.name)"
						$oUserSpec | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'user_name' -Value "$($PSBoundParameters['UserName'])@$($oDomain.name)@internal-authz"
						#$oUserSpec | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'domain' -Value $([PSCustomObject]@{'id'=$oDomain.Id})
						$oUserSpec | Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name 'domain' -Value $([PSCustomObject]@{'name'=$oDomain.name})
					}Else{
						#For Other ID Authentication Sources when I have a Sandbox to write/test
					}
					
					#Send to Server
					Resolve-oVirtConnection -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName | Out-Null
					$Token = $(($oVirtConnections | ?{$_.Name -eq $oVirtServerName}).ExtensionData.access_token)
					$Headers = @{"Accept" = "application/json";"Authorization" = "Bearer $($Token)"; "All-Content"="true"}
					#$Headers = @{"Accept" = "application/xml";"Authorization" = "Bearer $($Token)"; "All-Content"="true"}
					$Uri = $BaseURL + "/ovirt-engine/api/users"
					$Method = "POST"
					$JsonBody = $oUserSpec | ConvertTo-Json -Depth 50
					#$JsonBody | ConvertFrom-Json2Xml
					#($oUserSpec | ConvertTo-Json | ConvertFrom-Json2Xml)
					Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand): Submitting Json to Create oUser"
					Write-Verbose "$($JsonBody | Out-String)"
					$NewoGroup = $Null
					TRY{$NewoGroup = Invoke-RestMethod -Uri $Uri -Headers $Headers -Method $Method -Body $JsonBody -ContentType "application/json" -EV WebError}Catch{$FormattedWebError = (Format-WebError -WebError $WebError -Body $JsonBody -Uri $Uri); $OutPutItems.Add($FormattedWebError) | Out-Null; Write-Error $FormattedWebError}
					IF($NewoGroup){
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand): Created oUser"
						$OutPutItems.Add((Convert-RestResponseTooVirtObject -InputObject $NewoGroup -ObjectType "oUser" -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName)) | Out-Null
						Update-oVirtServer_LastUsedTime -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName
					}Else{
						Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand): Error [$($WebError | Out-String)]"
					}
				}Else{
					Write-Warning "oDomain Type [$($oDomain.GetType().Name)]"
				}
			}Else{
				Write-Warning "Could not find an oDomain matching the provided input paraameters, quitting..."
			}
		}
	}
	End{
		Write-Verbose "$($MyInvocation.MyCommand): End"
		IF($OutPutItems.Count -gt 1){$OutPutItems}ElseIF($OutPutItems.Count -eq 1){$OutPutItems[0]}
	}
}

Function New-oVM{
	<#
		.SYNOPSIS
			This function creates an OLVM (oVirt) Kernel-based Virtual Machine
		.DESCRIPTION
			This function creates an OLVM (oVirt) Kernel-based Virtual Machine
		.PARAMETER Name
			The Name of the VM
		.PARAMETER VMType
			Virtual machine type 'desktop' intended to be used as a desktop, implication is that a sound device will automatically be added to the virtual machine
			Virtual machine type 'server' intended to be used as a server, implication is that a sound device will NOT automatically be added to the virtual machine
			Virtual machine type 'high_performance' intended to be used as a high performance virtual machine, implication is that the virtual machine configuration 
			will automatically be set for running with the highest possible performance, and with performance metrics as close to bare metal as possible
			 
			 * Some of the recommended configuration settings for the highest possible performance
			 * cannot be set automatically; manually setting them before running the virtual machine is recommended.
			 *
			 * The following configuration changes are set automatically:
			 *
			 * - Enable headless mode.
			 * - Enable serial console.
			 * - Enable pass-through host CPU.
			 * - Enable I/O threads.
			 * - Enable I/O threads pinning and set the pinning topology.
			 * - Enable the paravirtualized random number generator PCI (virtio-rng) device.
			 * - Disable all USB devices.
			 * - Disable the soundcard device.
			 * - Disable the smartcard device.
			 * - Disable the memory balloon device.
			 * - Disable the watchdog device.
			 * - Disable migration.
			 * - Disable high availability.
			 *
			 * The following recommended configuration changes have to be set manually by the user:
			 *
			 * - Enable CPU pinning topology.
			 * - Enable non-uniform memory access (NUMA) pinning topology.
			 * - Enable and set huge pages configuration.
			 * - Disable kernel same-page merging (KSM).
		.PARAMETER InstanceType
			The Instance Type of a VM is a set of predefined sizes to use to define a new VM instead of citing them individually
			For example `medium` instance type includes 1 virtual CPU and 4 GiB of memory
			The attributes that are used for instance
			 * types and are common to virtual machine and template types are:
			 *
			 * - `console`
			 * - `cpu`
			 * - `custom_cpu_model`
			 * - `custom_emulated_machine`
			 * - `display`
			 * - `high_availability`
			 * - `io`
			 * - `memory`
			 * - `memory_policy`
			 * - `migration`
			 * - `migration_downtime`
			 * - `os`
			 * - `rng_device`
			 * - `soundcard_enabled`
			 * - `usb`
			 * - `virtio_scsi`
			 *
			 * When creating a virtual machine from both an instance type and a template, the virtual machine
			 * will inherit the hardware configurations from the instance type
			 *
			 * NOTE: An instance type inherits it's attributes from the template entity although most template
			 * attributes are not used in instance types
			Options: 'tiny', 'small', 'medium', 'large', 'xlarge', 'custom_maybe_in_the_future'
		.PARAMETER oTemplate
			The name of the template to model the VM
		.PARAMETER oTemplateId
			The id of the template to model the VM
		.PARAMETER CloneTemplatePermissions
			Specifies if the permissions of the template should be copied to the virtual machine.
			If this optional parameter is provided, the permissions of the template (only the direct ones, not 
			the inherited ones) will be copied to the created virtual machine
		.PARAMETER BaseVMSpecsOnly
			This is a special parameter that ignores all settings Except -Name and -oCluster, and builds a bare 
				minimum oVM using the default "Blank" Template
		.PARAMETER ForkTemplateDisk
			Specifies if the virtual machine should be a dependent of the template.
			When a virtual machine is created from a template the disks of the virtual machine can depend on 
			the disks of the template, they are using the copy on write mechanism so that only the differences from 
			the template take up real storage space. 
			
			If this parameter is NOT specified the disks of the created virtual machine will be cloned, and 
			independent of the template, using this parameter will the virtual machine should be dependent on the template 
			disk.
		.PARAMETER Comment
			Populates the Comment field of the oVM in OLVM
		.PARAMETER Description
			Populates the Description field of the oVM in OLVM
		.PARAMETER OSType
			The Operating System to be used on the VM
			IntelliSense (tab ahead) Can provide list, same list as in OLVM drop-down options
			Default is 'Oracle Linux 8.x x64 [ol_8x64]'
		.PARAMETER oCluster
			The name of the destination cluster to place the VM
		.PARAMETER oClusterId
			The Id of the destination cluster to place the VM
		.PARAMETER oHost
			The name(s) of the destination Host(s) to place the VM.
			Pin VM To Host(s)
				Allows a VM to be required to stay on a host
				* - Controlled physical hardware configuration for VM (e.g NUMA, CPU, NICs…).
				* - Prevent VM migration, satisfying administrative constraints. Such as: licensing, physical proximity, optimize CPU utilization, network optimization
		.PARAMETER oHostId
			The Id(s) of the destination Host(s) to place the VM.
			Pin VM To Host(s)
				Allows a VM to be required to stay on a host
				* - Controlled physical hardware configuration for VM (e.g NUMA, CPU, NICs…).
				* - Prevent VM migration, satisfying administrative constraints. Such as: licensing, physical proximity, optimize CPU utilization, network optimization
		.PARAMETER MigrationMode
			Valid options are 'migratable', 'pinned', 'user_migratable'
		.PARAMETER oStorageDomain
			The Name of the Storage Domain to place the boot disk
		.PARAMETER oStorageDomainId
			The Id of the Storage Domain to place the boot disk
		.PARAMETER NoDisk
			OverRides all disk entries (including defaults) and creates oVM container with no disk attached
		.PARAMETER DiskSize
			The Disk size of the boot disk in bytes
		.PARAMETER DiskType
			Valid options are 'image', 'cinder', 'lun', 'managed_block_storage'
		.PARAMETER DiskFormat
			Valid options are 'cow', 'raw'
		.PARAMETER DiskInterface
			Valid options 'virtio', 'ide', 'sata', 'spapr_vscsi', 'virtio_scsi'
		.PARAMETER DiskDataType
			Valid options 'data', 'system'
		.PARAMETER DiskName
			The name of the Boot disk, default is "OS_Disk"
		.PARAMETER DiskComment
			The Comment on the Boot disk, default is "Boot Disk"
		.PARAMETER DiskDescription
			The Description on the Boot disk, default is "Boot Disk"
		.PARAMETER Memory
			The size of the granted memory in bytes, default is 
		.PARAMETER MemoryGuaranteed
			The amount of memory, in bytes, that is guaranteed to not be drained by the balloon mechanism.
			The oVirt Engine internally rounds this value down to whole MiB (1MiB = 220 bytes).
			It can be updated while the virtual machine is running since oVirt 4.2 onwards, provided memory 
			is updated in the same request as well, and the virtual machine is in state up.
		.PARAMETER MemoryMax
			Maximum virtual machine memory, in bytes.
			The user provides the value in bytes, and the oVirt Engine rounds the value down to the nearest 
			lower MiB value.
			For example, if the user enters a value of 1073741825 (1 GiB + 1 byte), then the oVirt Engine 
			will truncate that value to the nearest lower MiB boundary: in this case 1073741824 (1 GiB).
		.PARAMETER MemoryBallooning
			Enables Memory Ballooning Feature
			Memory balloon is a guest device, which may be used to re-distribute / reclaim the host memory 
			based on VM needs in a dynamic way. In this way it’s possible to create memory over commitment states.
			NOTE: Enable Memory Balloon Optimization must also be selected for the cluster to be active
		.PARAMETER MemoryOverCommitPercentage
			Set Memory OverCommit Percentage allowed
			The amount of memory page sharing allowed of the memory from the virtual machine to other virtual machines
			Note: Memory Ballooning must be enabled to allow memory overcommitment
			See: https://docs.oracle.com/en/virtualization/oracle-linux-virtualization-manager/admin/admin-gs-optimize.html#config-vm-mem-cpu
		.PARAMETER MemoryTHPEnabled,
			Transparent HugePage Support (THP) is an alternative mean of using huge pages for the backing of 
			virtual memory with huge pages that supports the automatic promotion and demotion of page sizes 
			and without the shortcomings of hugetlbfs.
		.PARAMETER FirstBootDevice
			Valid options are 'cdrom', 'hd', 'network'
			Default is 'hd'
		.PARAMETER SecondBootDevice
			Valid options are 'cdrom', 'hd', 'network'
		.PARAMETER CpuType
			Valid options are 'x86_64', 'ppc64', 's390x'
			Default is 'x86_64'
		.PARAMETER CpuSockets
			The socket configuration can be updated without rebooting the virtual machine. 
			The cores and the threads require a reboot
			Default is 1
		.PARAMETER CpuCoresPerSocket
			Default is 1
		.PARAMETER CpuThreads
			Default is 1
		.PARAMETER CPUShares
			Valid options are 'disabled', 'low', 'medium', 'high', 'custom'
			'low', 'medium', 'high'
			'low':512
			'medium':1024
			'high':2048
		.PARAMETER CPUSharesInt,
			If CPUShares is set to custom, this setting allows for specific integer
		.PARAMETER CustomCPU
			Allows override of cluster default CPU type, provides a mask to advanced CPU chipset features
			IntelliSense (tab ahead) Can provide list, same list as in OLVM drop-down options
			Valid options are 'Nehalem','Nehalem,+spec-ctrl,+ssbd','Westmere','Westmere,+pcid,+spec-ctrl,+ssbd',
			'SandyBridge','SandyBridge,+pcid,+spec-ctrl,+ssbd,+md-clear','IvyBridge','IvyBridge,+pcid,+spec-ctrl,+ssbd,+md-clear',
			'Haswell-noTSX','Haswell-noTSX,+spec-ctrl,+ssbd,+md-clear','Broadwell-noTSX','Broadwell-noTSX,+spec-ctrl,+ssbd,+md-clear',
			'Skylake-Client,-hle,-rtm,-mpx','Skylake-Client-noTSX-IBRS,+ssbd,+md-clear,-mpx','Skylake-Server,-hle,-rtm,-mpx',
			'Skylake-Server-noTSX-IBRS,+ssbd,+md-clear,-mpx','Cascadelake-Server,-hle,-rtm,-mpx','Cascadelake-Server-noTSX,-mpx',
			'Icelake-Server-noTSX,-mpx'
			
		.PARAMETER CustomEmulatedMachine
			IntelliSense (tab ahead) Can provide list, same list as in OLVM drop-down options
			Valid options are 'isapc','microvm','pc','pc-i440fx-1.4','pc-i440fx-1.5','pc-i440fx-1.6','pc-i440fx-1.7','pc-i440fx-2.0',
			'pc-i440fx-2.1','pc-i440fx-2.10','pc-i440fx-2.11','pc-i440fx-2.12','pc-i440fx-2.2','pc-i440fx-2.3','pc-i440fx-2.4',
			'pc-i440fx-2.5','pc-i440fx-2.6','pc-i440fx-2.7','pc-i440fx-2.8','pc-i440fx-2.9','pc-i440fx-3.0','pc-i440fx-3.1',
			'pc-i440fx-4.0','pc-i440fx-4.1','pc-i440fx-4.2','pc-i440fx-5.0','pc-i440fx-5.1','pc-i440fx-5.2','pc-i440fx-6.0',
			'pc-i440fx-6.1','pc-i440fx-6.2','pc-i440fx-7.0','pc-i440fx-7.1','pc-i440fx-7.2','pc-q35-2.10','pc-q35-2.11','pc-q35-2.12',
			'pc-q35-2.4','pc-q35-2.5','pc-q35-2.6','pc-q35-2.7','pc-q35-2.8','pc-q35-2.9','pc-q35-3.0','pc-q35-3.1','pc-q35-4.0',
			'pc-q35-4.01','pc-q35-4.1','pc-q35-4.2','pc-q35-5.0','pc-q35-5.1','pc-q35-5.2','pc-q35-6.0','pc-q35-6.1','pc-q35-6.2',
			'pc-q35-7.0','pc-q35-7.1','pc-q35-7.2','q35','x-remote'
		.PARAMETER CustomCompatibilityVersion
			See: https://www.ovirt.org/documentation/upgrade_guide/
		.PARAMETER CpuProfile
			The name of the CPU profile available at the cluster to assign the VM
		.PARAMETER CpuProfileId
			The Id of the CPU profile available at the cluster to assign the VM
		.PARAMETER NumaNodeCount
			Manually Set the Number of Virtual Numa Nodes
			See: https://www.ovirt.org/develop/release-management/features/sla/numa-and-virtual-numa.html
		.PARAMETER oNicName
			The name of the first oNic
			Default is "oNic0"
		.PARAMETER oNicComment
			The Comment field of the first oNic
		.PARAMETER oNicDescription
			The Description field of the first oNic
		.PARAMETER oNicType
			The type of the first oNic
			Valid options are 'virtio', 'e1000', 'pci_passthrough', 'rtl8139', 'rtl8139_virtio', 'spapr_vlan'
			Default is 'virtio'
		.PARAMETER oVNicProfile
			The oVNicProfile Name to attach to the first oNic
			This is the VLAN Network Name to connect to the oNic
		.PARAMETER oVNicProfileId
			The oVNicProfile Id to attach to the first oNic
		.PARAMETER oNicLinkedEnable
			Enables oNic Link State On
		.PARAMETER oNicPluggedEnable
			Enables oNic Plugged In State
		.PARAMETER oNicConnectOnBoot
			Enable oNic to be connected at boot time
		.PARAMETER CustomMACaddress
			Valuse to set the oNic MAC address to use instead of an auto generated value
		.PARAMETER AttachCD
			Enables checkbox to attach a CD
				Valid options 'StartConnected', 'StartDisConnected'
		.PARAMETER BootCDImage
			The Name of the ISO file to use as a permanent boot image
		.PARAMETER BootCDImageId
			The ID of the ISO file to use as a permanent boot image
		.PARAMETER ChangeCD
			Connect or Remove an ISO file in the virtual CD tray
			This is a temporary activity to allow live connections to ISO files
				Valid options 'Connect', 'Eject'
		.PARAMETER ActiveCDImage
			The Name of the ISO file to 'insert' into the virtual CD tray
		.PARAMETER ActiveCDImageId
			The ID of the ISO file to 'insert' into the virtual CD tray
		.PARAMETER TimeZone
			TimeZone to set the VM container clock
			IntelliSense (tab ahead) Can provide list, same list as in OLVM drop-down options
			Valid options are "(GMTZ) Greenwich Standard Time [Etc/GMT]","(GMT-12:00) Dateline Standard Time [Etc/GMT+12]",
			"(GMT-10:00) Hawaaiian Standard Time [Pacific/Honolulu]","(GMT-09:00) Alaskan Standard Time [America/Anchorage]",
			"(GMT-08:00) Pacific Standard Time [America/Los_Angeles]","(GMT-07:00) Mountain Standard Time [America/Denver]",
			"(GMT-07:00) US Mountain Standard Time [America/Phoenix]","(GMT-06:00) Central America Standard Time [America/Guatemala]",
			"(GMT-06:00) Central Standard Time [America/Chicago]","(GMT-06:00) Canada Central Standard Time [America/Regina]",
			"(GMT-06:00) Central Standard Time (Mexico) [America/Mexico_City]","(GMT-05:00) SA Pacific Standard Time [America/Bogota]",
			"(GMT-05:00) Eastern Standard Time [America/New_York]","(GMT-04:00) Atlantic Standard Time [America/Halifax]",
			"(GMT-04:00) Pacific SA Standard Time [America/Santiago]","(GMT-04:00) Venezuela Standard Time [America/Caracas]",
			"(GMT-04:00) SA Western Standard Time [America/La_Paz]","(GMT-03:30) Newfoundland Standard Time [America/St_Johns]",
			"(GMT-03:00) E. South America Standard Time [America/Sao_Paulo]","(GMT-03:00) SA Eastern Standard Time [America/Buenos_Aires]",
			"(GMT-02:00) Mid-Atlantic Standard Time [Atlantic/South_Georgia]","(GMT-02:00) Greenland Standard Time [America/Godthab]",
			"(GMT-01:00) Azores Standard Time [Atlantic/Azores]","(GMT-01:00) Cape Verde Standard Time [Atlantic/Cape_Verde]",
			"(GMTZ) GMT Standard Time [Europe/London]","(GMT+01:00) W. Europe Standard Time [Europe/Berlin]",
			"(GMT+01:00) Central Europe Standard Time [Europe/Budapest]","(GMT+01:00) Central European Standard Time [Europe/Warsaw]",
			"(GMT+01:00) Romance Standard Time [Europe/Paris]","(GMT+01:00) W. Central Africa Standard Time [Africa/Lagos]",
			"(GMT+01:00) W. Central Africa Standard Time [Africa/Algiers]","(GMT+02:00) E. European Standard Time [Asia/Nicosia]",
			"(GMT+02:00) Egypt Standard Time [Africa/Cairo]","(GMT+02:00) GTB Standard Time [Europe/Bucharest]",
			"(GMT+02:00) FLE Standard Time [Europe/Helsinki]","(GMT+02:00) South Africa Standard Time [Africa/Johannesburg]",
			"(GMT+02:00) Israel Standard Time [Asia/Jerusalem]","(GMT+03:00) E. Africa Standard Time [Africa/Nairobi]",
			"(GMT+03:00) Arab Standard Time [Asia/Riyadh]","(GMT+03:00) Russian Standard Time [Europe/Moscow]",
			"(GMT+03:00) Arabic Standard Time [Asia/Baghdad]","(GMT+03:00) Turkey Standard Time [Europe/Istanbul]",
			"(GMT+03:30) Iran Standard Time [Asia/Tehran]","(GMT+04:00) Caucasus Standard Time [Asia/Yerevan]",
			"(GMT+04:00) Arabian Standard Time [Asia/Dubai]","(GMT+04:00) Georgian Standard Time [Asia/Tbilisi]",
			"(GMT+04:30) Afghanistan Standard Time [Asia/Kabul]","(GMT+05:00) West Asia Standard Time [Asia/Tashkent]",
			"(GMT+05:00) Ekaterinburg Standard Time [Asia/Yekaterinburg]","(GMT+05:30) India Standard Time [Asia/Calcutta]",
			"(GMT+05:30) Sri Lanka Standard Time [Asia/Colombo]","(GMT+05:45) Nepal Standard Time [Asia/Katmandu]",
			"(GMT+06:00) Central Asia Standard Time [Asia/Dhaka]","(GMT+06:30) Myanmar Standard Time [Asia/Rangoon]",
			"(GMT+07:00) North Asia Standard Time [Asia/Krasnoyarsk]","(GMT+07:00) SE Asia Standard Time [Asia/Bangkok]",
			"(GMT+07:00) N. Central Asia Standard Time [Asia/Novosibirsk]","(GMT+08:00) W. Australia Standard Time [Australia/Perth]",
			"(GMT+08:00) China Standard Time [Asia/Shanghai]","(GMT+08:00) Taipei Standard Time [Asia/Taipei]",
			"(GMT+08:00) North Asia East Standard Time [Asia/Irkutsk]","(GMT+08:00) Singapore Standard Time [Asia/Singapore]",
			"(GMT+09:00) Yakutsk Standard Time [Asia/Yakutsk]","(GMT+09:00) Korea Standard Time [Asia/Seoul]",
			"(GMT+09:00) Tokyo Standard Time [Asia/Tokyo]","(GMT+09:30) AUS Central Standard Time [Australia/Darwin]",
			"(GMT+09:30) Cen. Australia Standard Time [Australia/Adelaide]","(GMT+10:00) West Pacific Standard Time [Pacific/Port_Moresby]",
			"(GMT+10:00) Vladivostok Standard Time [Asia/Vladivostok]","(GMT+10:00) Tasmania Standard Time [Australia/Hobart]",
			"(GMT+10:00) AUS Eastern Standard Time [Australia/Sydney]","(GMT+10:00) E. Australia Standard Time [Australia/Brisbane]",
			"(GMT+11:00) Central Pacific Standard Time [Pacific/Guadalcanal]","(GMT+12:00) Fiji Standard Time [Pacific/Fiji]",
			"(GMT+12:00) New Zealand Standard Time [Pacific/Auckland]","(GMT+13:00) Tonga Standard Time [Pacific/Tongatapu]",
			"(GMT+13:00) Samoa Standard Time [Pacific/Apia]"
			
			Default is "(GMTZ) Greenwich Standard Time [Etc/GMT]"
		.PARAMETER HAEnabled
			Enable HA on oVM
			
			Several conditions must be satisfied in order to start such a VM safely and consistently with user actions.
			The very first condition is that oVirt Engine must be fully certain that the VM is not running anywhere at the moment. Failing to satisfy this condition could lead to multiple instances of the VM running concurrently on different hosts, so called split brain situation. oVirt uses safety mechanisms such as sanlock data, VM leases and resume behaviors to prevent split brain. But it’s still important to be aware that if oVirt Engine doesn’t know (under certain setups) for sure that a VM is not already running, it can’t start it automatically elsewhere. For instance, if a host running a VM is unreachable it doesn’t mean that the VM is not happily running there. If corresponding protection mechanisms are not enabled then oVirt Engine may not be able to start the VM elsewhere, despite it is highly available.
			VMs manually shut down or powered off from oVirt, from the guest operating system, or by admin-issued host shutdown (which counts as user initiated shutdown) are not restarted automatically. Switching VMs off manually is a user action and oVirt honors it. The user is responsible for starting such a VM again manually.
			There may be other reasons preventing start of a highly available VM, such as impossibility to run the VM due to resource constraints at a given moment.
			See: https://www.ovirt.org/develop/ha-vms.html
		.PARAMETER HAPriority
			Set HA Priority on oVM
			Valid options are 'Low', 'Medium', 'High'
			Default is 'High'
		.PARAMETER LeaseStorageDomain
			The Name of the Lease Storage Domain for HA
			A lease is a Sanlock resource residing on a special volume on the storage domain, this Sanlock resource is used to provide storage base locking.
			
			This feature adds the ability to acquire a lease per VM on shared storage without attaching the lease to a disk. 
			A VM lease, provides two important capabilities; avoiding split-brain, and starting a VM on another host if the 
			original host becomes non-responsive. The latter capability will be used to improve availability of HA VMs.
			
			See: https://www.ovirt.org/develop/release-management/features/storage/vm-leases.html
		.PARAMETER LeaseStorageDomainId
			The Id of the Lease Storage Domain for HA
		.PARAMETER WatchDogModel
			The watchdog device can be used to detect guest crash or hang, and if ‘dump’ is chosen for the action of watchdog timeout, libvirt will dump guest’s memory on timeout automatically.
			
			A virtual hardware watchdog device can be added to the guest via the the “devices” configuration. And only one watchdog device is supported for each VM.
			When a watchdog device is active and take action, the vdsm will log this event.
			The watchdog device requires an additional driver and management daemon in the guest. Just enabling the watchdog in the vdsm “devices” configuration does not do anything useful on its own.
			'i6300esb'    default model, emulating a PCI Intel 6300ESB
		.PARAMETER WatchDogAction
			The optional action attribute describes what action to take when the watchdog expires. Valid values are specific to the underlying hypervisor.
			  'reset'          forcefully reset the guest 
			  'shutdown'       gracefully shutdown the guest (not recommended)
			  'poweroff'       forcefully power off the guest
			  'pause'          pause the guest
			  'none'           default, do nothing
			  'dump'           automatically dump the guest
		.PARAMETER MigrationAutoConverge
			Busy enterprise workloads hosted on large sized VM’s tend to dirty memory faster than the transfer rate achieved via live guest migration. Despite some good recent improvements (& using dedicated 10Gig NICs between hosts) the live migration may NOT converge.
			Recently support was added in qemu (version 1.6) to allow a user to choose if they wish to force convergence of their migration via a new migration capability : “auto-converge”. This feature allows for qemu to auto-detect lack of convergence and trigger a throttle-down of the VCPUs.
			
			Valid options are 'inherit', 'true', 'false'
			Default is 'inherit'
			
			See: https://www.ovirt.org/develop/release-management/features/virt/xbzrle-and-auto-convergence.html
		.PARAMETER MigrationCompressed
			Enable compression of repeated pages during live migration
			Valid options are 'inherit', 'true', 'false'
			Default is 'true'
		.PARAMETER MigrationEncrypted
			Enable native TLS encryption of live migrations
			Valid options are 'inherit', 'true', 'false'
			Default is 'inherit'
		.PARAMETER MigrationParallel
			Allows Parallel Migrations
			Valid options are 'inherit', 'auto', 'auto_parallel','disabled','custom'
			Default is 'inherit'
			
			A new migration option to enable parallel migration connections is introduced in cluster and VM edit dialogs. The cluster option specifies what to use in the given cluster. VMs can override the cluster value individually. The new option offers the following choices:
			* - Disabled (the default in clusters): Parallel migration connections are not used.
			* - Auto: Use or do not use parallel migration connections and set their number automatically based on the available resources (network bandwidth and CPU power).
			* - Parallel: Always use parallel migration connections (for the supposed benefit of a more efficient implementation over non-parallel implementation) and set their number automatically based on the available resources (network bandwidth and CPU power).
			* - Custom: Use parallel migration connections and use the number of connections specified by the user. The minimum number of connections is 2. There is no upper limit but it is recommended not to use more than 16 and the actual number of connections used for a particular migration is restricted to the number of threads on the source and destination hosts (whichever is lower).
			* - Cluster value (only in the VM edit dialog; it’s the default there): Use parallel connections as specified in the VM’s cluster settings.
		.PARAMETER BiosBootMenuEnabled
			Enables Boot Menu in VM BIOS, allows selection of Boot Device or entry into virtual BIOS settings
		.PARAMETER BiosType
			Selection of Bios types
			Valid options are 'I440FX Chipset with BIOS [i440fx_sea_bios]', 'Q35 Chipset with BIOS [q35_sea_bios]', 'Q35 Chipset with UEFI [q35_ovmf]', 'Q35 Chipset with UEFI SecureBoot [q35_secure_boot]'
			Default is 'Q35 Chipset with UEFI SecureBoot [q35_secure_boot]'
		.PARAMETER Stateless
			Enable virtual machine Stateless option
			Disks are rolled-back after shutdown, no persistent data retention on local drives
		.PARAMETER DeleteProtected
			Enable virtual machine deletion protection (blocking)
		.PARAMETER MultiQueuesEnabled
			If `true`, each virtual interface will get the optimal number of queues, depending on the available virtual Cpus
		.PARAMETER HeadlessMode
			Allows running VM without virtual peripherals, VM must be managed via OS connection options, no console
		.PARAMETER VideoType
			Select emulated video system
			Valid options are 'vga', 'cirrus'
			Default is 'vga'
		.PARAMETER GraphicsProtocol
			The protocol for remote console access
			Valid options are 'vnc','spice'
			Default is 'vnc'
		.PARAMETER VNCKeyboardLayout
			Keyboard layout selection for remote console
			Valid options are 'ar', 'da', 'de', 'de-ch', 'en-gb', 'en-us', 'es', 'et', 'fi', 'fo', 'fr', 'fr-be', 'fr-ca', 'fr-ch', 'hr', 'hu', 'is', 'it', 'ja', 'lt', 'lv', 'mk', 'nl', 'no', 'pl', 'pt', 'pt-br', 'ru', 'sl', 'sv', 'th', 'tr'
			Default is 'en-us'
		.PARAMETER ConsoleDisconnectAction
			Action to take on the console of the oVM, if connection is interrupted
			Valid options are 'NONE','LOCK_SCREEN','LOGOUT','SHUTDOWN','REBOOT'
		.PARAMETER DisconnectActionDelayinMinutes
			Delay time for Console Disconnect Action in Minutes
		.PARAMETER Monitors
			Number of monitors for oVm
			Default is 1
			
			Ability to channel Spice display protocol up to 4 different PCI channels in a single VM
			Traditionally support for multiple monitor was handled via a single PCI channel, I.e. user could select up to 4 monitors and the VM handle that via a single PCI analog to one physical display adapter that is attach to a mother board via a single PCI express slot. This feature let the user decide if he want one PCI slot for each monitor or using the legacy multiple monitor support.
			oVirt will support only cluster 3.3 and higher and only for Qxl (Spice) display type, VNC display type is not supported for this feature. Only Linux based OS will support this feature.
		.PARAMETER DisplayAllowOverRide
			Enable Console Display OverRide
		.PARAMETER DisplayCopyPasteEnabled
			Enable Console Display Copy/Paste feature
		.PARAMETER DisplayFileTransferEnabled
			Enable Console Display File Transfer feature
		.PARAMETER SmartCardEnabled
			Support pass through of Smartcard attached to client to a virtual machine
			Allow the VM owner or administrator to specify if a virtual machine should support smartcard
			Allow the VM user (on portal) to be able to disable this setting
		.PARAMETER UsbEnabled
			Allows an oVM to connect to a USB device on the oHost
			Note: The VM must be pinned to host and this hook will fail any migration attempt.
			Host attached USB devices can be viewed with lsusb
		.PARAMETER Sso
			Reference to the Single Sign On configuration this virtual machine is configured for
			The user can be automatically signed in the virtual machine's operating system when console is opened
		.PARAMETER VirtIOSerialConsoleEnabled
			Allow direct ssh access to the virtual serial consoles of the VMs managed by an oVirt engine instance, using a SSH proxy server.
			 This feature will allow users to directly connect to the VM’s serial consoles, emulated through virtio channels, using ssh, without directly accessing Engine
			 Engine will still be used by in background to learn about VM placement, and to store authentication keys
		.PARAMETER PassThroughHostCPU
			Enable Pass-Through Host CPU
			Displayed in Host side-tab of the VM dialog
			This option can only be enabled when VM live migration is disabled
		.PARAMETER AutoPinningPolicy
			The CPU and NUMA pinning policy
			Valid options are 'adjust','disabled','existing'
			* - adjust		The CPU and NUMA pinning will be configured by the dedicated host
			* - disabled	The CPU and NUMA pinning won’t be calculated
			* - existing	The CPU and NUMA pinning will be configured by the virtual machine current state.
		.PARAMETER CPUPinningPolicy
			Set CPU Pinning Policy
			CPU pinning is the ability to run specific VM’s virtual CPU (vCPU) on specific physical CPU (pCPU) in a specific host.
			Valid options are 'none','Resize_and_Pin_Numa','dedicated','isolate_threads'
		.PARAMETER TPMDeviceEnabled
			Enable emulated Trusted Platform Module (TPM) device
			TPM devices are useful to perform certain cryptographic operations (generating cryptographic keys, random numbers, hashes, etc.) or to store data that can be used to verify current software configuration securely. QEMU and libvirt implement, among other, support for emulated TPM 2.0 devices, which is what oVirt uses to add TPM devices to VMs.
			Once an emulated TPM device is added to the VM, it can be used as a normal TPM 2.0 device in the guest OS.
			Limitation: TPM devices can be used only with UEFI BIOS
		.PARAMETER IOThreadsEnabled
			Enable disk I/O Threads
			In case the IO Threads are enabled, all the disks which have VirtIO interface will be pinned to an IO thread 
			using a round robin algorithm, e.g. for 4 disks and 2 threads it will be:
				disk 1 -> iothread 1
				disk 2 -> iothread 2
				disk 3 -> iothread 1
				disk 4 -> iothread 2
		.PARAMETER NumberIOThreads
			The Number of disk I/O Threads, if enabled
			Default is 1 but user can provide custom setting 
		.PARAMETER StartPaused
			Enable StartPaused Feature (used for accessing the boot manager)
		.PARAMETER VirtIOSCSIEnabled
			Enable VirtIO SCSI
			The virtio-scsi feature is a new para-virtualized SCSI controller device. It is the foundation of an 
			alternative storage implementation for KVM Virtualization’s storage stack
			Virtio-SCSI devices will obtain a number of queues depending on the available virtual Cpus and disks, or 
			according to the specified virtioScsiMultiQueues
			Benefits:

			* - Improved scalability—virtual machines can connect to more storage devices (the virtio-scsi can handle multiple block devices per virtual SCSI adapter).
			* - Standard command set—virtio-scsi uses standard SCSI command sets, simplifying new feature addition.
			* - Standard device naming—virtio-scsi disks use the same paths as a bare-metal system. This simplifies physical-to-virtual and virtual-to-virtual migration.
			* - SCSI device passthrough—virtio-scsi can present physical storage devices directly to guests.
			Virtio-SCSI provides the ability to connect directly to SCSI LUNs and significantly improves scalability 
			compared to virtio-blk. The advantage of virtio-SCSI is that it is capable of handling hundreds of devices 
			compared to virtio-blk which can only handle approximately 30 devices and exhausts PCI slots
		.PARAMETER VirtIOSCSIMultiQueues
			Enable VirtIO SCSI Multi Queues
			Enable Multi Queues per Virtual Interface (Multi Queues Enabled).
			Valid options 'disabled','automatic','custom'
		.PARAMETER VirtIOSCSIMultiQueuesCustomCount
			Set the number of VirtIO SCSI Queues if enabled
		.PARAMETER SerialNumberPolicy
			Specify a serial number policy for the virtual machines in the cluster.

			Following options are supported:
			vm - Sets the virtual machine’s UUID as its serial number.
			host - Sets the host’s UUID as the virtual machine’s serial number.
			custom - Allows you to specify a custom serial number in serial_policy_value.
			SystemDefault - Default setting to use cluster level instead of VM explicit setting
		.PARAMETER CustomSerialNumber
			The Custom Serial Number assigned when SerialNumberPolicy is set to 'custom'
		.PARAMETER AffinityGroup
			The Name of the Affinity Group to add oVM
		.PARAMETER AffinityLabel
			The Name of the Affinity Label to add oVM
		.PARAMETER VmStorageErrorResumeBehaviour
			If the storage, on which this virtual machine has some disks gets unresponsive, the virtual machine gets paused
			Possible options, what should happen with the virtual machine in the moment the storage gets available again
			
			leave_paused
				Do nothing with the virtual machine
				Useful if there is a custom failover implemented and the user does not want the virtual machine to get resumed
			auto_resume
				The virtual machine gets resumed automatically in the moment the storage is available again
			kill
				The virtual machine will be killed after a timeout (configurable on the hypervisor)
				This is the only option supported for highly available virtual machines
				with leases. The reason is that the highly available virtual machine is
				restarted using the infrastructure and any kind of resume risks
				split brains
		.PARAMETER RandomGeneratorEnabled
			Enable Random Number Generator device configuration for this virtual machine
		.PARAMETER RandomGeneratorDurationMs
			The Random Generator Duration in MiliSeconds
			Range 1 - 2147483647
		.PARAMETER RandomGeneratorBytesPerSec
			The Random Generator Bytes Per Second
			Range 1 - 2147483647
		.PARAMETER hugepages
			VM huge page size in KB
			Range 0 - 2147483647
			The virtual machine’s huge page size must be the same size as the pinned host’s huge page size.
			The virtual machine’s memory size must fit into the selected size of the pinned host’s free huge pages.
			The NUMA node size must be a multiple of the huge page’s selected size.
		.PARAMETER sndbuf
			Enter the size of the buffer for sending the virtual machine’s outgoing data over the socket. Default value is 0.
			Range 1 - 9
			Set the huge page size to the largest size supported by the pinned host.
			The recommended size for x86_64 is 1 GB.
			WARNING: Increasing the value of the sndbuf custom property results in increased occurrences of communication failure between hosts and unresponsive virtual machines.
		.PARAMETER vhost
				Disables vhost-net, which is the kernel-based virtio network driver on virtual network interface cards attached to the virtual machine.
				To disable vhost, the format for this property is LogicalNetworkName: false.
				This will explicitly start the virtual machine without the vhost-net setting on the virtual NIC attached to LogicalNetworkName.
				
				vhost-net provides better performance than virtio-net, and if it is present, it is enabled on all virtual machine NICs by default.
				Disabling this property makes it easier to isolate and diagnose performance issues, or to debug vhost-net errors; for example, if migration 
				fails for virtual machines on which vhost does not exist.
		.PARAMETER sap_agent
			Enable SAP Monitoring
		.PARAMETER nvram_template
		.PARAMETER viodiskcache
			Caching mode for the virtio disk. writethrough writes data to the cache and the disk in parallel, writeback does not copy modifications 
			from the cache to the disk, and none disables caching.
			Valid options 'none','writeback','writethrough'
		.PARAMETER extra_cpu_flags
		.PARAMETER qemu_cmdline
		.PARAMETER scsi_hostdev
			Optionally, if you add a SCSI host device to a virtual machine, you can specify the optimal SCSI host device driver. For details, see Adding Host Devices to a Virtual Machine.
			Valid options 'scsi_generic','scsi_block','scsi_hd','virtio_blk_pci'

			scsi_generic: (Default) Enables the guest operating system to access OS-supported SCSI host devices attached to the host. Use this driver for SCSI media changers that require raw access, such as tape or CD changers.
			scsi_block: Similar to scsi_generic but better speed and reliability. Use for SCSI disk devices. If trim or discard for the underlying device is desired, and it’s a hard disk, use this driver.
			scsi_hd: Provides performance with lowered overhead. Supports large numbers of devices. Uses the standard SCSI device naming scheme. Can be used with aio-native. Use this driver for high-performance SSDs.
			virtio_blk_pci: Provides the highest performance without the SCSI overhead. Supports identifying devices by their serial numbers.
		.PARAMETER oVirtServerName
			The Name of the target oVirt Server (Oracle Linux Virualtization Manager)(OLVM) system to place the new oVM
		.EXAMPLE
			$NewoVM = New-oVM -Name "DeleteMe" -oCluster Default -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName -NoDisk
				To Remove Test oVM
				Remove-oVM -Id $NewoVM.Id -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName -Confirm:0
		.EXAMPLE
			$NewoVM = New-oVM -Name "DeleteMe" -oCluster Default -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName -DiskFormat cow -DiskSize 1048576 -DiskType image -DiskInterface virtio
		.EXAMPLE
			**NOT Working**
			$NewoVM = New-oVM -Name DeleteMe -oTemplate ((Get-oTemplate)[0]).Name -oCluster ((Get-oCluster)[0]).Name  -oVirtServerName $oVirtServerName
		.INPUTS
			[System.String]
			[System.Security.SecureString]
			[System.Management.Automation.PSCredential]
			[System.Array]
			[HashTable]
			[Int32]
			[PSObject]
			[PSCustomObject]
			[System.Security.SecureString]
			[System.Management.Automation.PSCredential]
		.OUTPUTS
			[System.String]
			[oVM]
		.NOTES
			See David A. Stewart <itsavant@gmail.com>.
